Teachers estimated the amount of time they had spent on 20 health issues on the day of the survey. The average time spent on all health issues was 73.58 min in Year 1 and 35.86 min in Year 2. The top five health issues and average minutes spent per day in Year 1 were (a) other (22.82); (b) calling parents (5.77); (c) aches/pains (5.51); (d) sleep issues (5.48); and (e) congestion (4.23). During the second year, the top five health issues and minutes spent per day on each were (a) calling parents (4.26); (b) stomach ache (4.11); (c) aches/pains (3.41); (d) cuts/sores (3.29); and (e) lice (2.18; Table 2
). Anecdotal comments by the teachers regarding health issues ranged from “this is a calm day! [I] usually address issues on a daily basis and need nurse’s advice/input” and “it is my professional opinion that too much instructional time is wasted while taking care of students health needs on a daily basis”; to more descriptive comments such as:

My student w/a diagnosed mental health issue was absent today. Both my assistant and I spent a great deal of time with her. When the school nurse is available, sometimes those students w/aches, pains, etc. are okay and don’t seek more attention after they have seen the nurse. When she is here it is really cuts down on the minutes I spend dealing with the “boomerang” cases (those with little aches & pains who keep coming back to tell the teacher).
